THIS IS MY NOTE WHEN READING THIS BOOK

The and operator (&&) evaluates to true, only if both conditions given to it are true. if the first condition is false, then the whole condition must be false.
The or operator (||) evaluates to true, if either condition given to it is true. It knows that if the first condition is true, the whole condition must be true.
! is the not operator. It reverses the value of a condition. 

switch statements can replace a sequence of if statements. The switch statement will only check a single value, can’t use a switch statement to check a string of characters or any kind of array.

do while loop is another form of the while loop that checks the loop condition after the loop body is run. That means the loop always executes at least once.

Remember: counter++ means “increase the counter variable by one.”
Remember: counter-- means “decrease the counter variable by one.”

A break statement will break you straight out of the current loop, skipping whatever follows it in the loop body.
Breaks can be useful because they’re sometimes the simplest and best way to end a loop. But you might want to avoid using too many, because they can also make the code a little harder to read.

break: get out from here :))
continue: skip the rest of the loop body and go back to the start of the loop
If the condition on a loop is the value 1, then the loop will run forever.

In C, the keyword void means it doesn’t matter.

A pointer is just the address of a piece of data in memory.

If you declare a variable inside a function like main(), the computer will store it in a section of memory called the stack.
If a variable is declared outside any function, it will be stored in the globals section of memory.
A variable declared inside a function is usually stored in the stack.
A variable declared outside a function is stored in globals.

Memory structure: STACK-->HEAP-->GLOBAL-->CONSTANTS-->CODE

If you want to find out the memory address of the variable, you can use the & operator. Eg: printf("x is stored at %p\n", &x);
The address of the variable tells you where to find the variable in memory. That’s why an address is also called a pointer, because it points to the variable in memory.

sizeof can tell you how many bytes of space something takes in memory.
Factos: sizeof is operator, not function.
        An operator is compiled to a sequence of instructions by the compiler. A function has to jump to a separate piece of code.

On 32-bit operating systems, a pointer takes 4 bytes of memory and on 64-bit operating systems, a pointer takes 8 bytes.
On most systems, if p is a pointer and you want to store it in a long variable a, you can type a = (long)p

Fact: int num[] --> int[] and int* num; array is also pointer
      array[i] = *(array + i)
Arrays begin with index 0. The index is just the number that’s added to the pointer to find the location of the element.

scanf() accept pointer because it going to update the contents of input so it need address.
scanf() can limit the data entered by add the size to the format string.
When scanf() reads a string with the %s, it stops as soon as it hits a space. if you want to enter more than one word, you either have to call it more than once, or use some fancy regular expression trick.

fgets() is an alternative to scanf()
fgets() can read the whole string include space, vv...

==> If you need to enter structured data with several fields, you’ll want to use scanf(). If you’re entering a single unstructured string, then fgets() is probably the way to go.

strchr() - find location of char in string
strcmp() - compare two strings
strstr() - find location of string in string
strcpy() - copy string to another
strlen() - return length of string
strcat() - Concatenate two strings

DO ONE THING AND DO IT WELL - Unix philosophy

printf("Foo"); == fprintf(stdout/stderr, "Foo"); The fprintf() function allows you to choose where you want to send text to.
">" redirects the Standard Output, "2>" redirects the Standard Error, "<" redirects the Standard Input

"|" (This is the pipe that connects the processes.)
if write "(./Foo | ./Bar < baz.txt > qux.txt)" it will:
     - Connect Foo and Bar together, can treat as a single program.
     - Both of the programs will run at the same time; as output is produced by the first program, it can be consumed by the second program.
     - The < will send a file’s contents to the first process in the pipeline. The > will capture the Standard Output from the last process in the pipeline.
     - The parentheses will make sure the data file is read by the Standard Input of the Foo program.

Create a new data stream using the fopen() function
     FILE *in_file = fopen("input.txt", "r"); This will create a data stream to read from a file.
     FILE *out_file = fopen("output.txt", "w"); This will create a data stream to write from a file.
     FILE *append_file = fopen("output.txt", "a"); This will create a data stream to append from a file.
After that we can use fprintf and fscanf to printf or read contents from file
     fprintf(out_file, "Your mom is %s and %s\n", foo, bar);
     fscanf(in_file, "%d", &foo);
When you’re finished with a data stream, you need to close it.
     fclose(in_file);
     fclose(out_file);
(The truth is that all data streams are automatically closed when the program ends, but it’s still a good idea to always close the data stream yourself)

If the compiler finds a call to a function it hasn’t heard of, it will assume the function returns an int.
Function declarations tell the compiler what your functions will look like before you define them.

Using extern to share function between source files

gcc tips:
    gcc -c *.c
    gcc -o foo *.o
 This can help reduce the compilation time for the large project with many source files by compile only changed file and re-link the program.